A fresh cauliflower will be pure white and will be wrapped in crisp, bright green leaves. In particular, you should pay close attention to the base of the cauliflower. Regardless of how dirty or dingy the top looks, the base should be as white as possible. The color of the base is the best indication of how fresh the vegetable is. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/e/ec/Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/aid3206490-v4-728px-Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The floret tops along the outside of the head should be fairly compact. If they are loose, or if there are wide gaps between the tops, this could be an indication that the cauliflower has already started to go bad. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ec/Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/e/ec/Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/aid3206490-v4-728px-Steam-Cauliflower-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
